<section xml:id="notes-india">
  <title>Ancient Indian Mathematics (5.3)</title>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Indeterminate-Equations">
    <title>Indeterminate Equations</title>

    <p>
        Unlike China, the Indian subcontinent was rarely unified and was frequently divided into small empires with their own languages and cultures. Thus to speak of Indian mathematics refers is to speak of a mathematics from a wide variety of linguistic and cultural contexts, much like if we speak about European mathematics during the Middle Ages and Renaissance. 
    </p>

    <p>
        There are many similarities between India and Europe. Both regions consisted of many diverse peoples and languages who shared a common religion (Hinduism for India and Christianity for Europe) and a common language for intellectual communication (Sanskrit for India and Latin for Europe).
    </p>

     </subsection>

  </section>